						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Here is some of the general priciples of gearing that I have found.
<br />

<br />
1-Have an alchemist buddy.  The market is too fickle to afford the poisons you need consistently.  They are often either overpriced or not be had.  Additional strategies here are getting the apoth series of books and then you can make your own inks for your adept III's (your jeweler will love this and may demand it).  The real reason you are doing this is also to acquire rare loams. You will want those.  Buy them too when you see them for cheap.
<br />
 General Poison strategy:
<br />
  -The best Parsed DPS: forget damage up front.  Fights last, thus the only crucial aspect of a poison is how much damage will it contribute to the course of the fight?  Generally it is has been agreed that it is usually the low up front damage ones that have the highest potential output.  This however is only true if you are a kiter.  If, as the new combat system suggests you are a toe-to-toe fighter then I would a high up front one.  Why?  Because (and please correct me if i am mistaken) the poison will re-proc every 2.5-4 seconds, because it will hit 1 out of every four times, thus since you are striking so much in melee and you want to have those big drops near the end with your CA's, you might want to go for a front loading poison... Heck you could always carry both for that crucual situation.
<br />

<br />
  -Use a poison debuff: Get that poison rocking!
<br />
  -Carry some touch of the beholder (a stun potion ya!) these are precious and should be used for when soloing tough kiting fights that you want to have some distance between you.  Works HORRIBLE when fighting larger groups because your target gets stunned and falls behind group thtat is chasing you and then you are often out of range for bow strike.
<br />

<br />
Its all about versititiltity... 
<br />

<br />
Totems are a nice way to keep you moving quick (totem of the wolf) and at my level regenerating helath quicker (totem of the tiger) these combine to make a very effective escape combo.  If you need to run from a fight and dont want to ecav, consider that when you pansy scream for help you will be flipped into non-combat mode.  Thus your wolf form activates, meaning you are moving faster and better able to avoid your foes, plus your tiger forms additional regen will provide a safety buffer for the few stray hits the mob does put on you... Plus, it will usually outprocess any poison so it is an effective cure for most such...
<br />

<br />
Armor: For playemade buy the imbued chest and legs.  The rest fo your armor should generally come from drops and quests; the stats will be more specifically relevent  to your class and the cost is far less, a 1/10-1/4 depending upon your tastes.  THe imbued stuff is great thuogh, the stats are generally scout worth in the strength/agil/stamina categories and the imbuements again are another buffer between yourself and a poison or stray hits while kiting.  PGT is also nice here becasue the occasional might of the land that processess is like having your own personsal healer!  That is the scouts soloists bane, fragile hitpoints and no potential to heal oneself; thus pick equipment that will do it for you <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Rings: imbued are alright but they are a little cumbersome to always set off.  There are often better choices.  Like the slayer rings.  Up attack speed and confer great stats.  PLus do not require activation.  That means that when you an d your party have just died and are rebuffing you are putting your time into putting your poisons on (and sometimes potions to up your levelishness).  True the rings can be fired while you are moving and the stats are decent but...  I think th eless buffs you need to apply the more you can get at the game.  PLus that is one less thing that could desert you in a fight.
<br />

<br />
Basically the princple in gearing is to push your self up to higher levelishnes. I say levelishness because level is somewhat arbitrary, really what matters is stats.  I can outfight people in my class that are five levels higher because I use gear and potions that tweak me up and poisons to lower my enemies levelishness.  Two side equation.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
